(prosper Loan Data)¶

    by (Ahmed Aredah)

Project Describtion¶

Data Set¶

This data set contains 113,937 loans with 81 variables on each loan, including loan amount, borrower rate (or interest rate), current loan status, borrower income, and many others.

The data set is filtered to affecting variables only and records with NAN/NA values are deleted.

Project Output¶

In this explanatory study, we tend to study and address the following questions:

What factors affect a loans outcome status?

What affects the borrowers APR or interest rate?

Are there differences between loans depending on how large the original loan amount was?

Preliminary Wrangling¶

Dataset Structure¶

The dataframe has 113937 rows and 81 columns

The main feature(s) of interest in the dataset¶

The main features are features that are causing AmountDelinquent to increase or the LoanStatus to be Past Due.

Features of interest investigation¶

The features of interest are the ones affecting either AmountDelinquent and LoadStatus

Univariate Exploration¶

Past Due, Defaulted and Charged off loans (not payed back) are very frequent.

Not payed back Loans portions are quite large compared to payed

Employment Status definitely affects how they pay back the loan.

  • The most frequent Duration for the current employement status is 5 years.
  • Higher numbers are also available but with very low rate.
  • More investigation on Employement Status and Duratio is needed
  • Home Improvement is the most frequent
  • Debt Consolidation is among the most frequent category after the home improvement
  • Debt Consolidation means they failed to pay off a past loan, that means they may tend to not pay again
  • The most frequent Borrower Income Range is the mid range.
  • Higher Income Range are also available with lower frequency than the mid range
  • Monthly distribution is skewed to the right
  • Delinquent Amount distribution is skewed to the right
  • There is a big portion of borrowers tend to not pay back the loan until 5 years.
  • The most frequent term is 36 months.
  • The most frequent borrower rate is 15%
  • Loan Delinquent distribution is skewed to the left.
  • Loan Amount is bimodal around 3K and 13K.

    • Variable(s) distribution(s) discussion¶

    Most distributions are normal (in some cases: after applying a transformation)

    Tidness of the data¶

    Some Variables distributions are very skewed to the left/right. Log/log10 are applied in such cases

    Bivariate Exploration¶

    Borrowers tend to borrow loans, in most cases, up to 20 times greater than their income and in rare cases, up to 100 times greater than their income.

    Yet the majority of Loan borrowers falls in a lower range (between 0 to 10 times more than their income)

    To better understand what forces borrowers from not paying loans back. we need to filter only The number of days delinquent that is more than a year.

    Observed Relationships¶

    There is no direct relationship between the features

    Interesting Relationships¶

    Borrower Interest rate is directly correlated to the following:

  • Lend Yield
  • Estimated Effective Yield
  • Estimated Loss
  • Estimated Return

    • Borrowers rate is very correlated to the lender yield. That means they may be exactly equal.

    Employment Status seems to be affecting the estimated effective yield.

    The more the stable employment status is, the more the estimated effective yield

    The estimated loss seems to be not affected by the employment status

    The estimated return seems to be not affected by the employment status

    Multivariate Exploration¶

    These categories are less probable to pay in time

    These categories are much probable to pay in time

    The less the grade the borrower is, the more probable that the borrower does not return the borrowed money on time.

    The less the term duration is, the more monthly payment the borrowers have to pay.

    Relationship¶

    Borrower Interest rate is strongly correlated to the following:

  • Lend Yield
  • Estimated Effective Yield
  • Estimated Loss
  • Estimated Return
